message.content: We can factor the quadratic equation to obtain $(x-1)(x-6)<0$. We see that the quadratic is negative when the product $(x-1)(x-6)$ is negative. This occurs when either $(x-1)<0$ and $(x-6)>0$ or $(x-1)>0$ and $(x-6)<0$. The first case has $1<x<6$, and the second has $x<1$ or $x>6$. Combining these with an OR, we find $x \in \boxed{(1, 6)} \cup \boxed{(-\infty, 1) \cup (6, \infty)}$.
